The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after a sharp fall in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries of the region, are convinced democrats, depressing the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents from the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in the Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but rising sharply compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
